# Day 60 – Task A-3 (Part 2): Non-Technical Control Assessments — Examine and Interview | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## The Human and Process Side of Assessment

Day 59 covered the technical assessment activities — AWS infrastructure review, application testing, and configuration analysis. Four findings emerged: two Moderate, two Low. Today completes the Task A-3 assessment work with the non-technical methods: document examination and stakeholder interviews.

This distinction matters more than it might initially appear. Technical testing determines whether controls are *configured*. Examination and interviews determine whether controls are *operating* — whether the configured technical controls are supported by the human and process infrastructure that gives them continuity and meaning.

A session timeout configured at 15 minutes is a technical fact. Whether clinical staff are trained on why the timeout exists, whether they understand the downtime procedure when the session times out mid-encounter, and whether they know how to report an incident they observe — these are operational realities that only examination and interviews can surface.

NIST SP 800-53A is explicit that all three assessment methods — examine, interview, and test — are required for a thorough assessment of High-impact systems. An assessment that only tests technical controls misses the process and human layer where many of the most consequential security gaps actually live.

