## What Actually Clicked for Me

The concept that clarified non-technical assessment today is the difference between *compliance* and *capability*.

Compliance means the control exists — the policy is written, the procedure is documented, the training record shows completion. Capability means the control works — the personnel responsible for executing the control understand their role, can describe the procedure accurately, and have evidence that they have executed it.

An assessor who only examines documents for compliance can conclude that an organization has a documented incident response plan, a training program, and an access review procedure. An assessor who also interviews stakeholders may discover that key personnel cannot accurately describe the incident escalation threshold, that the access review is executed by a single person with no backup who has no documentation of how the review is conducted, or that the training content does not reflect the actual threats the system faces.

None of those gaps would appear in a document-only examination. All of them are genuine security program vulnerabilities. Interviews are the method that bridges the gap between documentation and operational reality.

