### Incident Response Plan (IR-1, IR-2, IR-3) — Document Examination

**Documents reviewed:** MyClinic Incident Response Plan (current version); tabletop exercise scenario, participant list, and after-action report; IRP version history.

**Examination findings:**

The IRP document is current, approved by the Executive Director, and covers the NIST SP 800-61 incident lifecycle. Three tabletop-driven improvements are documented in the version history — confirming the plan is a living document that evolves from testing. ✓

After-action report from the most recent tabletop reviewed. Finding from the tabletop: the clinical staff representative was not familiar with the manual patient registration process. This is documented in the after-action report as an action item — but the action item is "complete clinical downtime procedures (CP-2)" rather than "conduct interim training on manual registration." The gap between the identified finding and the action item is meaningful — the downtime procedure document is not yet complete, but some basic manual registration guidance could be provided to clinical staff immediately without waiting for the full procedure.

**Observation (not a finding):** The tabletop after-action tracking could be strengthened by adding target dates and responsible parties to each action item. Two of the three action items in the most recent after-action report list the action without a named owner or target date. This reduces accountability for follow-through.

The IRP does not include the HIPAA breach determination workflow as a separate section — this is the POA&M item [POA&M-IR1-01] identified in Day 51. The assessor confirms the POA&M accurately characterizes this gap. ✓ (POA&M item confirmed accurate — not a new finding.)

