## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The Health IT Manager's access review interview — specifically the focus on "do they still need access?" rather than "is the role still appropriate?" — reminded me of the circumstances surrounding one of the most common patterns in healthcare insider threat incidents.

The **2018 Michigan Medicine** insider breach involved a former employee who retained access to patient records after transitioning to a different role within the organization. The access review process confirmed that the individual was still employed and still needed some system access — but did not verify that the clinical record access level was still appropriate for the new role.

This is precisely the gap that Finding A-5 identifies. An access review that confirms employment and general system need but does not evaluate role accuracy will consistently miss the scenario where a user's job function no longer justifies their current access level. The fix — updating the review template to explicitly prompt role accuracy evaluation — is simple. The risk it addresses — clinical record access retained by users who no longer need it — is real.

The interview method was essential for surfacing this finding. The document examination showed that reviews were being conducted on schedule with Health IT Manager certification. Only the interview revealed that the certification was based on a narrower evaluation than the SSP intended.

