## What I Am Still Thinking About

The interview with the IT Administrator raised a question I want to think through before the preliminary findings meeting: how should the SAR characterize Finding A-7 in relation to Finding A-3?

Finding A-3 is the undocumented service account — a technical configuration gap. Finding A-7 is the process gap that allowed the service account to be created without ISSO awareness. They are related findings with the same root cause, but they are distinct — one is a current security exposure, the other is a systemic process gap that will produce future exposures if not corrected.

My instinct is that the SAR should present both findings but connect them explicitly — noting that A-7 is the root cause that enabled A-3 and that remediating only A-3 without remediating A-7 leaves the organization exposed to the same pattern recurring. The remediation recommendation should address both: correct the service account configuration (A-3) and update the change management procedure to require ISSO notification for IAM entity creation (A-7).

This kind of root cause linking is what distinguishes a useful SAR from a list of disconnected findings. An AO reading a SAR that presents seven separate findings has a harder time understanding the security picture than one that groups related findings, identifies root causes, and presents a coherent remediation narrative.

I want to discuss with the lead assessor whether the SAR format should include a root cause section that groups related findings — this would make the SAR more useful for the AO's authorization decision and more actionable for the remediation work.

